# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zephyr-rtos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The **ARM Cortex-M** is a group of 32-bit RISC ARM processor cores licensed by ARM Limited.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] These cores are optimized for low-cost and energy-efficient integrated circuits, which have been embedded in tens of billions of consumer devices.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Though they are most often the main component of microcontroller chips, sometimes they are embedded inside other types of chips too.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M family consists of Cortex-M0, Cortex-M0+, Cortex-M1, Cortex-M3, Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7, Cortex-M23, Cortex-M33, Cortex-M35P, Cortex-M52, Cortex-M55, Cortex-M85.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] A floating-point unit (FPU) option is available for Cortex-M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 cores, and when included in the silicon these cores are sometimes known as "Cortex-MxF", where 'x' is the core variant.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The ARM Cortex-M family are ARM microprocessor cores that are designed for use in microcontrollers, ASICs, ASSPs, FPGAs, and SoCs.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M cores are commonly used as dedicated microcontroller chips, but also are "hidden" inside of SoC chips as power management controllers, I/O controllers, system controllers, touch screen controllers, smart battery controllers, and sensor controllers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The main difference from Cortex-A cores is that Cortex-M cores have no memory management unit (MMU) for virtual memory, considered essential for "full-fledged" operating systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M programs instead run bare metal or on one of the many real-time operating systems which support a Cortex-M.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Though 8-bit microcontrollers were very popular in the past, Cortex-M has slowly been chipping away at the 8-bit market as the prices of low-end Cortex-M chips have moved downward.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M have become a popular replacements for 8-bit chips in applications that benefit from 32-bit math operations, and replacing older legacy ARM cores such as ARM7 and ARM9.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] In particular, the embedded wear-leveling controller inside most SD cards or flash drives is a (8-bit) 8051 microcontroller or ARM CPU.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] ARM Limited neither manufactures nor sells CPU devices based on its own designs, but rather licenses the processor architecture to interested parties.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Arm offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] To all licensees, Arm provides an integratable hardware description of the ARM core, as well as complete software development toolset and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Integrated Device Manufacturers (IDM) receive the ARM Processor IP as synthesizable RTL (written in Verilog).
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] In this form, they have the ability to perform architectural level optimizations and extensions.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] This allows the manufacturer to achieve custom design goals, such as higher clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions (including floating point), optimizations for size, debug support, etc.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] To determine which components have been included in a particular ARM CPU chip, consult the manufacturer datasheet and related documentation.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The architectures are binary instruction upward compatible from ARMv6-M to ARMv7-M to ARMv7E-M.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M3 / Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M3 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7 / Cortex-M33 / Cortex-M35P.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Only Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instruction sets are supported in Cortex-M architectures; the legacy 32-bit ARM instruction set isn't supported.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] All Cortex-M cores implement a common subset of instructions that consists of most Thumb-1, some Thumb-2, including a 32-bit result multiply.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 / Cortex-M23 were designed to create the smallest silicon die, thus having the fewest instructions of the Cortex-M family.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include Thumb-1 instructions, except new instructions (CBZ, CBNZ, IT) which were added in ARMv7-M architecture.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include a minor subset of Thumb-2 instructions (BL, DMB, DSB, ISB, MRS, MSR).
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 / M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P have all base Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instructions.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 adds three Thumb-1 instructions, all Thumb-2 instructions, hardware integer divide, and saturation arithmetic instructions.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M4 adds DSP instructions and an optional single-precision floating-point unit (VFPv4-SP).
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 adds an optional double-precision FPU (VFPv5).
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 add TrustZone instructions.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The 16-bit Thumb-1 instruction set has evolved over time since it was first released in the legacy ARM7T cores with the ARMv4T architecture.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] New Thumb-1 instructions were added as each legacy ARMv5 / ARMv6 / ARMv6T2 architectures were released.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 core is optimized for small silicon die size and use in the lowest price chips.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ is an optimized superset of the Cortex-M0.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ has complete instruction set compatibility with the Cortex-M0 thus allowing the use of the same compiler and debug tools.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ pipeline was reduced from 3 to 2 stages, which lowers the power usage and increases performance (higher average IPC due to branches taking one fewer cycle).
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] In addition to debug features in the existing Cortex-M0, a silicon option can be added to the Cortex-M0+ called the Micro Trace Buffer (MTB) which provides a simple instruction trace buffer.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ also received Cortex-M3 and Cortex-M4 features, which can be added as silicon options, such as the memory protection unit (MPU) and the vector table relocation.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The smallest ARM microcontrollers are of the Cortex-M0+ type (as of 2014, smallest at 1.6 mm by 2 mm in a chip-scale package is Kinetis KL03).
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M1 is an optimized core especially designed to be loaded into FPGA chips.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M4 is a Cortex-M3 plus DSP instructions, and optional floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] A core with an FPU is known as Cortex-M4F.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 is a high-performance core with almost double the power efficiency of the older Cortex-M4.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] It features a 6-stage superscalar pipeline with branch prediction and an optional floating-point unit capable of single-precision and optionally double-precision operations.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The instruction and data buses have been enlarged to 64-bit wide over the previous 32-bit buses.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] If a core contains an FPU, it is known as a Cortex-M7F, otherwise it is a Cortex-M7.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M23 is similar to a Cortex-M0+ plus integer divide instructions and TrustZone security features, and also has a 2-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M33 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M33 is similar to a cross of Cortex-M4 and Cortex-M23, and also has a 3-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M35P core was announced in May 2018 and based on the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] It is conceptually a Cortex-M33 core with a new instruction cache, plus new tamper-resistant hardware concepts borrowed from the ARM SecurCore family, and configurable parity and ECC features.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Currently, information about the Cortex-M35P is limited, because its *Technical Reference Manual* and *Generic User Guide* haven't been released yet.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M52 core was announced in November 2023 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually, it can be seen as a cross between the Cortex-M33 and the Cortex-M55.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] Key differences are that its Helium co-processor is single beat (the M55 is dual beat), and it has a 32-bit main bus similar to the M33 to ease transition of applications.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M55 core was announced in February 2020 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] It has a 4 or 5 stage instruction pipeline.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M85 core was announced in April 2022 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] The documentation for ARM chips is extensive.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] In the past, 8-bit microcontroller documentation would typically fit in a single document, but as microcontrollers have evolved, so has everything required to support them.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] A documentation package for ARM chips typically consists of a collection of documents from the IC manufacturer as well as the CPU core vendor (ARM Limited).
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturer datasheet for the exact physical chip.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturer reference manual that describes common peripherals and aspects of a physical chip family.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturers have additional documents, such as: evaluation board user manuals, application notes, getting started guides, software library documents, errata, and more.
[src:zephyr-rtos/arm-cortex-m] See External links section for links to official Arm documents.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] In computing, a **devicetree** (also written **device tree**) is a data structure describing the hardware components of a particular computer so that the operating system's kernel can use and manage those components, including the CPU or CPUs, the memory, the buses and the integrated peripherals.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] The device tree was derived from SPARC-based and PowerPC-based computers via the Open Firmware project.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] The current Devicetree specification is targeted at smaller systems and embedded systems, but is still used with some server-class systems (for instance, those described by the Power Architecture Platform Reference).
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Personal computers with the x86 architecture generally do not use device trees, relying instead on various auto configuration protocols (e.g.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Systems which use device trees usually pass a static device tree (perhaps stored in EEPROM, or stored in NAND device like eUFS) to the operating system, but can also generate a device tree in the early stages of booting.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] As an example, Das U-Boot and kexec can pass a device tree when launching a new operating system.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] On systems with a boot loader that does not support device trees, a static device tree may be installed along with the operating system; the Linux kernel supports this approach.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] The Devicetree specification is currently managed by a community named devicetree.org, which is associated with, among others, Linaro and Arm.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] A device tree can hold any kind of data as internally it is a tree of named nodes and properties.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Nodes contain properties and child nodes, while properties are name–value pairs.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Device trees have both a binary format for operating systems to use and a textual format for convenient editing and management.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Given the correct device tree, the same compiled kernel can support different hardware configurations within a wider architecture family.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] The Linux kernel for the ARC, ARM, C6x, H8/300, MicroBlaze, MIPS, NDS32, Nios II, OpenRISC, PowerPC, Power ISA, RISC-V, SuperH, and Xtensa architectures reads device tree information; on ARM, device trees have been mandatory for all new SoCs since 2012.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] This can be seen as a remedy to the vast number of forks (of Linux and Das U-Boot) that have historically been created to support (marginally) different ARM boards.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] The purpose is to move a significant part of the hardware description out of the kernel binary, and into the compiled device tree blob, which is handed to the kernel by the boot loader, replacing a range of board-specific C source files and compile-time options in the kernel.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] It is specified in a Devicetree Source file (.dts) and is compiled into a Devicetree Blob or device tree binary (.dtb) file (also known as the flattened device tree) through the Devicetree compiler (DTC).
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Device tree source files can include other files, referred to as device tree source includes.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] It has been customary for ARM-based Linux distributions to include a boot loader that necessarily was customized for specific boards, for example Raspberry Pi or Hackberry A10.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] This has created problems for the creators of Linux distributions as some part of the operating system must be compiled specifically for every board variant, or updated to support new boards.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] However, some modern SoCs (for example, Freescale i.MX6) have a vendor-provided boot loader with device tree on a separate chip from the operating system.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] A proprietary configuration file format used for similar purposes, the FEX file format, is a de facto standard among Allwinner SoCs.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Devicetree is widely used for ARM-based Android devices.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] BSD can support device tree, as device tree usually adopted on embedded devices.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Windows does not use Devicetree (DTB file) as described here.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Instead, it uses ACPI to discover and manage devices.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] On the boot process of iOS, iPadOS and ARM macOS, the Low-Level Bootloader (LLB) will load Apple-encrypted devicetree to main memory, then loads iBoot.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] The coreboot project makes use of device trees, but they are different from the flattened device trees used in the Linux kernel.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] In the example above, the line `/dts-v1/;` signifies version 1 of the DTS syntax.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] The tree has four nodes: `/` (root node), `soc` (stands for "system on a chip"), `flash-controller@4001e000` and `flash@0` (instance of flash which uses the flash controller).
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Besides these *node names*, the latter two nodes have *labels* `flash_controller` and `flash0` respectively.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] The latter two nodes have *properties*, which represent name/value pairs.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Property `label` has string type, property `erase-block` has integer type and property `reg` is an array of integers (32-bit unsigned values).
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Property values can refer to other nodes in the devicetree by their *phandles*.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Phandle for a node with label `flash0` would be written as `&flash0`.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Parts of the node names after the "at" sign (`@`) are *unit addresses*.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] Unit addresses specify a node's resource address in the address space of its parent node.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] The above tree could be compiled by the standard DTC compiler to binary DTB format or assembly.
[src:zephyr-rtos/device-tree] In Zephyr RTOS, however, DTS files are compiled into C header files (.h), which are then used by the build system to compile code for a specific board.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:zephyr-rtos/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] `**make menuconfig**` is one of five similar tools that can assist a user in configuring the Linux kernel before building, a necessary step needed to compile the source code.
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] `make menuconfig`, with a menu-driven user interface, allows the user to choose which features and modules to compile.
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] It is normally invoked using the command `make menuconfig`; menuconfig is a target in the Linux Makefile.
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] `make menuconfig` was not in the first version of Linux.
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] Prior to 2.5.45, the predecessor tool used Configuration Menu Language (CML) and was a question-and-answer-based utility (`make config`, `make oldconfig`).
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] All these tools use the **Kconfig** language internally.
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] Kconfig is also used in other projects, such as Das U-Boot, a bootloader for embedded devices, Buildroot, a tool for generating embedded Linux systems, and BusyBox, a single-executable shell utility toolbox for embedded systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] `make menuconfig` is generally more user-friendly compared to the question-and-answer-based configuration tool `make config`, and has a basic search system.
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] If the user is satisfied with a previous `.config` file, using `make oldconfig` uses this previous file to answer all questions that it can, only interactively presenting the new features.
[src:zephyr-rtos/kconfig] To use `make menuconfig`, Linux source is a requirement, a make tool, a C compiler, and the ncurses library.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The **Linux Foundation** (**LF**) is a non-profit organization established in 2000 to support Linux development and open-source software projects.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Linux Foundation started as Open Source Development Labs in 2000 to standardize and promote the open-source operating system kernel Linux.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] It merged with Free Standards Group in 2007.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The foundation has since evolved to promote open-source projects beyond the Linux OS as a "foundation of foundations" that hosts a variety of projects spanning topics such as cloud, networking, blockchain, and hardware.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The foundation also hosts annual educational events among the Linux community, including the Linux Kernel Developers Summit and the Open Source Summit.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] As of September 2015, the total economic value of the development costs of Linux Foundation Collaborative Projects was estimated at $5 billion.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] For the Linux kernel community, the Linux Foundation hosts its IT infrastructure and organizes conferences such as the Linux Kernel Summit and the Linux Plumbers Conference.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] It also hosts a Technical Advisory Board made up of Linux kernel developers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] One of these developers has been appointed to sit on the Linux Foundation board.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Linux Plumbers Conference has been held annually since 2008.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] It focuses on the Linux kernel and related tools and libraries, typically lasts 3 days, and was held in the USA primarily for USA-based developers in its early years, but now is regularly held elsewhere in the world.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In January 2016, the Linux Foundation announced a partnership with Goodwill Central Texas to help hundreds of disadvantaged individuals from underserved communities and a variety of backgrounds get the training they need to start careers in Linux IT.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In July 2020, the Linux Foundation announced an initiative allowing open-source communities to create Open Standards using tools and methods inspired by open-source developers.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Core Infrastructure Initiative (CII), is a project managed by the Linux Foundation that enables technology companies, industry stakeholders, and esteemed developers to collaboratively identify and fund critical open-source projects in need of assistance.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In June 2015, the organization announced financial support of nearly $500,000 for three new projects to better support critical security elements of the global information infrastructure.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In May 2016, CII launched its Best Practice Badge program to raise awareness of development processes and project governance steps that will help projects have better security outcomes.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In May 2017, CII issued its 100th badge to a passing project.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Introduced in October 2017, the Community Data License Agreement (CDLA) is a legal framework for sharing data.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] On March 3, 2009, the Linux Foundation announced that they would take over the management of Linux.com from its previous owners, SourceForge, Inc.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The site was relaunched on May 13, 2009, shifting away from its previous incarnation as a news site to become a central source for Linux tutorials, information, software, documentation, and answers across the server, desktop/netbook, mobile, and embedded areas.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] It also includes a directory of Linux software and hardware.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Much like Linux itself, Linux.com plans to rely on the community to create and drive content and conversation.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In 2020 amidst the COVID-19 pandemic, the Linux Foundation announced the LFPH, a program dedicated to advancing and supporting the virus contact tracing work led by Google and Apple and their Bluetooth notification systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The LFPH is focusing its efforts on public health applications, including the effort's first initiative: a notification app intended for governments wanting to launch their privacy-focused exposure notification networks.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] As of today, LFPH hosts two contact-tracing apps.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Allianz, Amazon, Microsoft, and S&P Global will be the initiative's founding members.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] LF Energy is an initiative launched by the Linux Foundation in 2018 to improve the power grid.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Linux Foundation Training Program features instructors and content from the leaders of the Linux developer and open-source communities.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Participants receive Linux training that is vendor-neutral and created with oversight from leaders of the Linux development community.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Linux Foundation's online and in-person training programs aim to deliver broad, foundational knowledge and networking opportunities.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In March 2014, the Linux Foundation and edX partnered to offer a free, massive open online class titled Introduction to Linux.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] This was the first in a series of ongoing free offerings from both organizations whose current catalogue of MOOCs include Intro to DevOps, Intro to Cloud Foundry and Cloud Native Software Architecture, Intro to Apache Hadoop, Intro to Cloud Infrastructure Technologies, and Intro to OpenStack.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In December 2015, the Linux Foundation introduced a self-paced course designed to help prepare administrators for the OpenStack Foundation's Certified OpenStack Administrator exam.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In early 2017, at the annual Open Source Leadership Summit, it was announced that the Linux Foundation would begin offering an Inclusive Speaker Orientation course in partnership with the National Center for Women & Information Technology.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In September 2020, the Linux Foundation released a free serverless computing training course with CNCF.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] It is taught by Alex Ellis, founder of OpenFaaS.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Among many other organizations with similar offerings, The Linux Foundation has reported a 40% increase in demand for their online courses in 2020 during the coronavirus pandemic and the resulting social-distancing measures.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The *patent commons* consists of all patented software which has been made available to the open source community.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] For software to be considered to be in the commons the patent owner must guarantee that developers will not be sued for infringement, though there may be some restrictions on the use of the patented code.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The concept was first given substance by Red Hat in 2001 when it published its Patent Promise.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Patent Commons Project was launched on November 15, 2005, by the Open Source Development Labs (OSDL).
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The core of the project is an online patent commons reference library aggregating and documenting information about patent-related pledges and other legal solutions directed at the open-source software community.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] As of 2015, the project listed 53 patents.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Linux Foundation's Open Compliance Program provides an array of programs for open-source software licensing compliance.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The focus of this initiative is to educate and assist developers (and their companies) on licensing requirements, to make it easier to create new software.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The program consists primarily of self-administered training modules, but it is also meant to include automated tools to help programmatically identify license compliance issues.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In December 2025, it was announced that the Linux Foundation will create the Agentic AI Foundation (AAIF) to host and ensure the open-source, interoperability of AI agents and having an organized product ecosystem.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] To establish the group, Anthropic is donating its Model Context Protocol (MCP), Block is donating Goose (an open source agent framework), and OpenAI is donating AGENTS.md (instructions that are added to code repositories instructing AI coding tools on how to act).
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Other organizations that are joining the foundation include: Amazon Web Services (AWS), Bloomberg, Cloudflare, and Google.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Funding for the Linux Foundation comes primarily from its Platinum Members, who pay US$500,000 per year according to Schedule A in LF's bylaws, adding up to US$7.5 million.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Gold Members contribute a combined total of US$1.2 million and Silver members contribute between US$5,000 and US$20,000 based on the amount of employees, summing up to at least US$6,240,000.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In December 2023, the Open Networking Foundation (ONF), including its LF Broadband, Aether and P4 projects, merged with Linux Foundation.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] As part of the merger, ONF handed over $5 million in funding.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] As of June 2024, the foundation collected annual fees worth at least US$14,940,000.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Linux Foundation established the Linux Foundation Europe, with its headquarter located in Brussels, on September 14, 2022, with the aim of promoting open source throughout Europe.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Linux Foundation Europe will increase open collaborative activities for all European stakeholders, including citizens, the public sector, and the private sector.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Among the first members of the Linux Foundation Europe are Ericsson, Accenture, Alliander, Avast, Bosch, BTP, esatus AG, NXP Semiconductors, RTE, SAP, SUSE S.A., TomTom, Bank of England, OpenForum Europe, OpenUK, and the Research Institutes of Sweden.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Linux Foundation Europe will make it possible for open collaborative projects to be housed on European soil.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The Linux Foundation Europe started the RISC-V Software Ecosystem (RISE) initiative on May 31, 2023.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] The goal of RISE is to increase the availability of software for high-performance and power-efficient RISC-V processors running high-level operating systems for a range of market segments by bringing together a large number of hardware and software vendors.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Red Hat, Samsung, Qualcomm, Nvidia, MediaTek, Intel, and Google are among the initial members.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Linux Foundation Europe organisation took over governance of open source Rust-based Servo browser engine project from Mozilla in 2020, then rebooted with Igalia in 2023.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Other projects include open source mobile cross platform framework, Open Mobile Hub as a middleware for cross platform mobile app interoperability across multiple mobile platforms launched in 2023.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] In India, the need for open-source technology has increased by 42% in 2023 as a result of the Linux Foundation's partnership with the International Startup Foundation (ISF).
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] They are also collaborating with the open source networking company OpenNets.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Through the LF Decentralized Trust, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and the Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology (MEITy) are utilizing Linux Foundation's projects to build the National Blockchain Framework and Digital Rupee.
[src:zephyr-rtos/linux-foundation] Linux Foundation India will provide open source contributors to the Linux Foundation's sub-organizations.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] It is named after Zephyrus, the ancient Greek god of the west wind.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] Zephyr originated from Virtuoso RTOS for digital signal processors (DSPs).
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] In 2001, Wind River Systems acquired Belgian software company Eonic Systems, the developer of Virtuoso.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] In November 2015, Wind River Systems renamed the operating system to *Rocket*, made it open-source and royalty-free.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] Compared to Wind River's other RTOS, VxWorks, Rocket had much smaller memory needs, especially suitable for sensors and single-function embedded devices.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] Rocket could fit into as little as 4 KB of memory, while VxWorks needed 200 KB or more.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] In February 2016, Rocket became a hosted collaborative project of the Linux Foundation under the name *Zephyr*.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] Wind River Systems contributed the Rocket kernel to Zephyr, but still provided Rocket to its clients, charging them for the cloud services.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] As a result, Rocket became "essentially the commercial version of Zephyr".
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] Since then, early members and supporters of Zephyr include Intel, NXP Semiconductors, Synopsys, Linaro, Texas Instruments, Nordic Semiconductor, Oticon, and Bose.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] As of January 2025, Zephyr had the largest number of contributors and commits compared to other RTOSes (including Mbed, RT-Thread, NuttX, and RIOT).
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] Zephyr intends to provide all components needed to develop resource-constrained and embedded or microcontroller-based applications.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] Zephyr uses Kconfig and devicetree as its configuration systems, inherited from the Linux kernel, but implemented in Python programming language for portability to non-Unix operating systems.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] The RTOS build system is based on CMake, which allows Zephyr applications to be built on Linux, macOS, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] Zephyr has a general-purpose tool called *West* for managing repositories, downloading programs to hardware, etc.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] Early Zephyr kernels used a dual nanokernel plus microkernel design.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] In December 2016, with Zephyr 1.6, this changed to a monolithic kernel.
[src:zephyr-rtos/zephyr-operating-system] A group is dedicated to maintaining and improving the security.
